There is an interesting claim about Rust:<p>> However, it prevents you from writing generic macros that use any l-value – we can’t write swap!(x[0], x[1]) as we could in Common Lisp.<p>As long as `macro_rules!` has existed (I could be wrong about before 0.8 though), you can wrote a macro that takes any expression, and will error from the assignment when the expression is not an lvalue:<p><pre><code>    macro_rules! swap {
        ($x:expr, $y:expr) => ({
            let tmp = $x;
            $x = $y;
            $y = tmp;
        })
    }</code></pre>
